Exercises

Data Introduction

Read the “music.csv” file into a dataframe named df. The dataset includes customer information for a fictitious music subscription service. The variables included are:

  • age (in years)
  • sex
  • household income (in US dollars)
  • annual miles driven in a car
  • number of children under 18 years old living at home
  • whether regularly commutes by car
  • reported enthusiasm for driving based on survey responses (rating is on a 1-to-7 scale with 7 being the highest)
  • reported enthusiasm for music based on survey responses (rating is on a 1-to-7 scale with 7 being the highest)
  • whether subscribes to the music service
  • a known assignment to one of the six customer segments based on prior research

Exercise 1 (10 Points)

  • Use the hclust() function in the cluster library to conduct hierarchical clustering for the data in df (excluding the “Segment” column)
  • Plot the complete cluster dendrogram
  • Based on the hierarchical clustering output, cut the data into 4 clusters and show the number of observations by cluster
music.q1<- read.csv("music.csv")
music1.df <- music.q1[,c(1:9)]



dist1 <- dist(as.matrix(music1.df))
## Warning in dist(as.matrix(music1.df)): NAs introduced by coercion
musicq1 <- hclust(dist1, method = "complete")
musicq1a <- hclust(dist1, method = "single")
plot(musicq1)

subgroup <- cutree(musicq1, k = 4)
table(subgroup)

Exercise 2 (10 Points)

  • Make a copy of df and name the new dataframe df.num
  • In df.num, recode the binary factors “sex”, “commuteCar”, and “subscribeToMusic” to numeric using the ifelse() function. For example, “subscribeToMusic” can be recoded to a numeric variable with numeric values 0s and 1s, where 0 indicates “subNo” and 1 indicates “subYes”
  • Use the kmeans() function to conduct kmeans clustering (with k = 4) for the data in df.num (excluding “Segment”)
  • What are the centers of the four clusters?
df.num <- na.omit(music.q1[,c(1:9)])
df.num$sex <- ifelse(music.q1$sex == "Male", 1, 0)
df.num$commuteCar <- ifelse(music.q1$commuteCar == "carNo", 0, 1)
df.num$subscribeToMusic <- ifelse(music.q1$subscribeToMusic == "subNo", 0, 1)

object.kmean <- kmeans(as.matrix(df.num),centers = 4 )
object.kmean$size
## [1]  50 297 333 215

Exercise 3 (10 Points)

  • Use the elbow method to determine the appropriate number of clusters for kmeans clustering of df.num (excluding “Segment”)
  • Create a line chart with the number of clusters (ranging from 1 to 20) as the horizontal axis and the average within-cluster sum of squared deviations from the cluster center as the vertical axis
  • Based on the elbow method, what is the appropriate number of clusters for kmeans clustering of df.num?
library(rlang)
## Warning: package 'rlang' was built under R version 3.6.1
library(purrr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'purrr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:rlang':
## 
##     %@%, as_function, flatten, flatten_chr, flatten_dbl,
##     flatten_int, flatten_lgl, flatten_raw, invoke, list_along,
##     modify, prepend, splice
wssmusic <- function(k) {
  kmeans(df.num, k, nstart = 10 )$tot.withinss
}

total.values <- 1:20


q2_values <- map_dbl(total.values, wssmusic)

?map_dbl()
## starting httpd help server ...
##  done
plot(total.values, q2_values,
       type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
       xlab="k number of clusters",
       ylab="total of sum of squares within cluster")

#Appropriate number of k mean clusters  = 4

Exercise 4 (10 Points)

  • For the k-means clustering of df.num (excluding “Segment”), create another line chart with the number of clusters (ranging from 1 to 20) as the horizontal axis and the percentage of variance explained (i.e. the ratio of the between-group variance to the total variance) as the vertical axis
  • Based on the elbow method, what is the appropriate number of clusters for kmeans clustering of df.num?
library(purrr)

wssmusic <- function(k) {
  kmeans(df.num, k)$betweens/kmeans(df.num, k)$totss
}

total.values <- 1:20


q2_values <- map_dbl(total.values, wssmusic)

plot(total.values, q2_values,
       type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
       xlab="k number of clusters",
       ylab="Variance")

Exercise 6 (10 Points)

  • For the Gaussian mixture model clustering of df.num (excluding “Segment”), create a line chart with the number of clusters (ranging from 1 to 20) as the horizontal axis and the BIC value of the Gaussian mixture model as the vertical axis
  • Based on the chart, what is the appropriate number of clusters for the Gaussian mixture model clustering of df.num?
library(purrr)
library(mclust)
wssmusic <- function(k) {
  Mclust(df.num, k )$bic
}

G.values <- 1:20

?map_dbl()
q2_values <- map_dbl(G.values, wssmusic)

plot(G.values, q2_values,
       type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
       xlab="number of clusters k ",
       ylab="sum of squares within clusters")

# if we use gausian mixtture models we get 6 as the total number of clusters

Exercise 9 (10 Points)

  • Use the randomForest() function in the randomForest library to build random forest (RF) models with 500 as the constant number of trees and varying mtry (i.e. number of variables randomly sampled as candidates at each split) to predict the customer segment (“Segment”) using other variables in the training data of Exercise 8
  • Create a line chart with the mtry (ranging from 1 to 9) as the horizontal axis and the corresponding accuracy rate on the testing data as the vertical axis
  • Based on the chart, what is the optimal value of mtry for your RF models?
library(randomForest)
## Warning: package 'randomForest' was built under R version 3.6.1
## randomForest 4.6-14
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
train2 <- sample(train)

q9 <- randomForest(Segment~subscribeToMusic+musicEnthuse+drivingEnthuse+commuteCar+kidsAtHome+milesDrive+householdIncome+sex+age, data = train2, maxnodes = 500 ,)


Forest.train <- predict(q9, train)
Forest.test <- predict(q9,test)

oob.values <- vector(length= 9)

for (k in 1:9) {
 storeitin <- randomForest(Segment~. ,data = train2, mtry = k, ntree= 500 )
 oob.values[k] <- storeitin$err.rate[nrow(storeitin$err.rate),1]
 
}

k <- 1:9

plot(k, oob.values,
       type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
       xlab="MTRY values",
       ylab="OOB")

#hence the best possible value would be 3 because oob is the lowest

Exercise 10 (10 Points)

  • Build a random forest model using the training data of Exercise 8 and the optimal value of mtry identified in Exercise 9
  • Use the heatmap.2() function to create a heat map of variable importance by segment
  • Based on the heat map, which variable is the most important predictor to identify customers in the “LongDistance” segment?
model.for.10 <- randomForest(Segment~subscribeToMusic+musicEnthuse+drivingEnthuse+commuteCar+kidsAtHome+milesDrive+householdIncome+sex+age, data = train, maxnodes = 500 , mtry = 3, importance = TRUE)

library(gplots)
